time revived, when Cornelia tenderly
approaching her, "Do I then embrace
<PB N="38" REF="42">
my &s;i&s;ter!" &s;aid &s;he, "United in &s;enti|ment,
are we al&s;o united in misfortune?"
<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 word"> with her &s;ighs, and their
<GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 word"> <GAP DESC="illegible" EXTENT="1 letter">hewed in mournful &s;ympathy to|gether.
At length Cornelia re&s;umed her narrative.</P>
<P>"My father, &s;truck with the conduct
of Hippolitus, pau&s;ed upon the offer.
The alteration in my health was too ob|vious
to e&s;cape his notice; the conflict
between pride and parental tenderne&s;s,
held him for &s;ome time in indeci&s;ion,
but the latter finally &s;ubdued every op|po&s;ing
feeling, and he yielded his con|&s;ent
to my marriage with Angelo. The
&s;udden tran&s;ition from grief to joy, was
almo&s;t too much for my feeble frame;
judge then what mu&s;t have been the ef|fect
of the dreadful rever&s;e, when the
news arrived that Angelo had fallen in
