lamp that &s;tood on a table, which
was almo&s;t the only furniture of the
<PB N="132" REF="136">
place. The count had advanced &s;eve|ral
&s;teps before he perceived an object,
which fixed all his attention. This
was the figure of a young woman lying
on the floor apparently dead. Her face
was concealed in her robe; and the long
auburn tre&s;&s;es which fell in beautiful
